## Verdict: PASS

No actionable findings.

## What passed on inspection

Shape D is implemented as specified. `Engine.open(...)` still resolves to just `Engine` in the TS surface, while `engine.openReport()` is a synchronous engine-attached accessor with the expected camelCase fields and no return-shape regression in either the native declaration or public wrapper ([binding.ts](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/ts/src/binding.ts:117), [index.ts](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/ts/src/index.ts:115), [index.ts](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/ts/src/index.ts:150)).

The Rust binding matches the native ground truth and the Python slice structurally: it adds sibling value types for `OpenReport`, `MigrationStepReport`, and `EmbedderIdentity`, stashes the native report at open time as `Arc<RustOpenReport>`, and converts from that stored snapshot on each accessor call. I did not find any nondeterministic conversion path that would break idempotency ([fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:541), [fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs:342), [fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs:428), [fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs:466)).

The TDD story is credible. On the baseline, TS had no `openReport()` on either `Engine` or `NativeEngine`, so the new test file would genuinely fail with `TS2339`; after the change, the test exercises the right acceptance path: spec-locked fields, repeated-call idempotency, and unchanged `Engine.open` Promise behavior ([baseline index.ts at 708a47f], [openreport.test.ts](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/ts/tests/openreport.test.ts:23), [openreport.test.ts](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/ts/tests/openreport.test.ts:49), [openreport.test.ts](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/src/ts/tests/openreport.test.ts:76)).

The spec/docs updates are consistent with the implementation: the TypeScript caveat is removed, the `Engine.open(...)` line is rewritten toward the accessor, `engine.openReport()` is added to the engine-attached list, and the parity-matrix row is now correctly `✅` for both bindings ([typescript.md](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/dev/interfaces/typescript.md:27), [typescript.md](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/dev/interfaces/typescript.md:45), [12-TX-parity-matrix.md](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/dev/notes/12-TX-parity-matrix.md:31), [acceptance.md](/tmp/fdb-0.6.1-OPENREPORT-ts-20260524T201023Z/dev/acceptance.md:1059)).

## Reviewer process notes

I inspected the required spec prompt, closure artifact, implementer commit, native Rust shape, TS binding/public surfaces, docs, parity matrix, and the sibling Python commit pattern. I did not rerun the TS or Rust test/build commands because the sandbox is read-only; the verify claims were checked by source inspection rather than independent execution.

`MEMORY.md` and repo-local `feedback_*.md` were not present in this worktree, so there was nothing additional to load from that channel.
